    "discriminators": [
     "A SUB-50 ms TRANSIENT. That is the entire definition. The gate length_seconds <= 0.2 does most of the work and it is a TRUE physical bound, not a tendency: a UI click that lasts a quarter of a second is not a click, it is something else.",
     "Attack under ~2 ms, high crest factor, no sustain, no pitch, sharply front-loaded envelope (envelope_temporal_centroid ~0.2).",
     "Against UIBeep: no pitch, no sustain. harmonicity < 0.35 combined with sustain_ratio < 0.25 rules out a beep outright.",
     "Against CMPTKey and MECHClik: physically the same event, and DSP can only narrow, not finish. A UI click is a SYNTHETIC, usually band-limited, single-transient event; a keyboard is a MECHANICAL, broadband, MULTI-transient train (key-down thock + key-up release). transient_count and onset_rate lean the call; text commits it.",
     "A dense STREAM of clicks (a scroll detent, a spinner, a counter) still gates on per-event length — but if the events are continuous and dense, check UIData instead."
    ],
