    "discriminators": [
     "'SCREEN GAK OR GARBLE' — a DENSE STREAM of micro-blips standing in for computation: scanning, thinking, calculating, text spitting onto a display. The morphology is a fast EVENT TRAIN, never a single event.",
     "The defining measurement is onset_rate_per_second — roughly 5-30/s, SUSTAINED for the length of the file. One blip is a UIBeep; one tick is a UIClick; MANY of them in a continuous stream is UIData. Count, not timbre.",
     "Partially PITCHED: the blips usually carry tone (harmonicity ~0.45), and that residual tonality is what separates data chatter from a glitch burst.",
     "Against UIGlitch: DATA is ORDERED and EVENT-LIKE (resolvable onsets, some periodicity, some tonality). GLITCH is DISORDERED and NOISY (high spectral_flatness, high flux, low harmonicity, no resolvable event grid). Order versus disorder is the axis.",
     "Against COMTelm: telemetry is the same idea for a REAL device, and the tell is bandwidth — telemetry is band-limited to the telephone channel (~3.4 kHz), UI data is full-bandwidth. If the file is a fax, modem or telegraph, prefer COMTelm."
    ],
